<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-582-816  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 582 816.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic News  June 25 1990 v36 n1815 p40(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Union hits U.S. firms in Malaysia. (AFL-CIO and InternationalLabor Rights Education and Research Fund petition U.S. governmentto punish alleged labor rights offenses of U.S. semiconductorfirms)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Ehrlich, Paul Charles.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The AFL-CIO and the International Labor Rights Education andResearch Fund are petitioning the U.S.andP;  government to revokeMalaysia's Generalized System of Preferences privileges due toalleged labor offenses by the Malaysian government and U.S.andO;semiconductor firms operating in that country.andP;  The petitionsargue that Malaysian unions are obstructed from striking, thatelectronics workers cannot form a national union, and thatminimum-wage and safety protection measures are violated.andP;  TheLabor Rights fund also claims that the Malaysian-AmericanElectronics Industry has directly blocked attempts to unionizeindustry companies and has threatened to relocate operations ifthe Malaysian government allows unions.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     MalaysiaSemiconductor industryAFL-CIOInternational tradeUnions.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>